passages.text: WSM closed down \(2.8\%\) (vs. the S&F 2%) following its 2Q beat and updated FY25 guidance, including a raise on the top line, while operating margin guidance was reiterated as the flow through from higher revenues is expected to be pressured by incremental tariff costs. Our key takeaways from the call include: 1) 2Q comps accelerated, with positive furniture comps driven by newness; 2) gross margin came in above expectations; and 3) WSM updated FY25 guidance, including a higher top line and reiterated operating margin expectations.

While furniture sales were positive for the second consecutive quarter and newness continues to resonate, we think the housing backdrop will continue to be a headwind and will keep growth rate tempered. We would also note that WSM is trading above its historical average at 21.6x NTM P/E, vs. its 3- year/5- year average of 14.5x/14.3x. We reiterate our Neutral rating on WSM with a price target of \(\) 203\$

WSM saw a comp increase of \(+3.7\%\) in 2Q25 vs. \(+3.4\%\) in 1Q25 and above consensus (LSEG Data & Analytics) at \(+2.0\%\) . The company called out drivers of its outperformance including positive comps in furniture and non- furniture and strong performance in its retail and eCommerce channels. Of note, 1Q25 was the first time WSM delivered a positive comp in its furniture business since 4Q22. For 2Q, we would also highlight that nominal PCE for furniture and household equipment grew \(+4.0\%\) , versus WSM's comp of \(+3.7\%\) . Additionally, furniture and home furnishing retail sales growth (y/y) increased by \(+5.1\%\) in July, accelerating from \(+4.5\%\) in June. By banner, West Elm experienced a sequential acceleration with a \(+3.3\%\) comp (vs. \(+0.2\%\) in 1Q), driven by positive comps in furniture and non- furniture along with +DD growth in newness. West Elm saw strength in its collection with Pierce & Ward, which is the banner's top selling collaboration to date. Pottery Barn delivered a \(+1.1\%\) comp (vs \(+2.0\%\) in 1Q), calling out positive initial reads from its fall launch and a strong customer response to innovation, while we note Pottery Barn had the lowest comp among the banners, despite lapping a \(- 7.1\%\) comp in 2Q24. Pottery Barn Children's reported a \(+5.3\%\) comp (vs. \(+3.8\%\) in 1Q), noting innovation has been key to delivering growth, while the banner's back- to- school business has also been

strong. Williams- Sonoma reported a \(+5.1\%\) comp (vs. \(+7.3\%\) in 1Q). WSM's B2B business grew \(+10\%\) in 2Q, accelerating from \(+8\%\) in 1Q, with both trade and contract delivering +DD comps.
Exhibit 1: WSM comp vs. furniture and household equipment nominal PCE (y/y)
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research, US Bureau of Economic Analysis (BEA)
Exhibit 2: WSM's B2B business growth (y/y)
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Gross margin came in above expectations: Gross margin increased \(+220\) bps y/y to \(47.1\%\) , above consensus at \(44.7\%\) , driven by higher merchandise margins (+190 bps) and supply chain efficiencies (+30 bps), with the occupancy rate flat to last year. Of note, improvement in merchandise margins were driven by select price increases and higher full price selling. 2Q results saw minimal impact from tariffs due to the company's mitigation efforts, including front loading lower tariff receipts in 1Q. In terms of supply chain efficiencies (Exhibit 3), WSM continues to realize expense savings across manufacturing, warehouse, and delivery, with a y/y improvement in key metrics. Inventory increased \(17.7\%\) y/y, including \(\) 70\(mn of strategic pull forward of receipts at lower tariff rates than expected later in FY25, along with\) \ \(20\) mn of incremental tariff costs recorded in inventory. Per management, \(50\%\) of the increase in inventory is related to tariffs, the majority of WSM's product is core, and the company is well- positioned from an in- stock and composition perspective to support sales growth.
Exhibit 3: In 2025, WSM saw a positive gross margin impact from supply chain efficiencies

WSM updated FY25 guidance, including a higher top line and reiterated operating margin expectations: WSM raised its FY25 top line guidance to revenue growth of \(+0.5\%\) to \(+3.5\%\) (vs. \(- 1.5\%\) to \(+1.5\%\) prior) and comps in the range of \(+2.0\%\) to \(+5.0\%\) (vs. flat to \(+3.0\%\) prior), with the midpoint above consensus at \(+2.1\%\) . Per management, the top line raise was driven by strong sales trends with a positive consumer response to newness/innovation, along with continued traction

across the company's key growth initiatives. Of note, the midpoint of guidance assumes a continuation of current trends, while management is encouraged by momentum in the business. Additionally, WSM reiterated its FY25 guidance to an operating margin of \(12.8\%\) , with the midpoint slightly below consensus at \(17.7\%\) . We would highlight that WSM finished 1H at a \(\sim 3.5\%\) comp, which is above the company's prior annual guidance (of \(+1.5\%\) at the midpoint). However, this incremental earnings flow through is expected to be offset by WSM's incremental tariff rate doubling to \(28\%\) (vs. \(14\%\) at the time of 1Q earnings in May). The incremental tariff costs include the \(30\%\) China tariff, \(50\%\) India tariff, \(20\%\) Vietnam tariff, \(18\%\) average tariff on the rest of the world, \(50\%\) steel and aluminum tariff, and \(50\%\) copper tariff. While WSM is anticipating an acceleration of tariff impacts throughout the year, likely pressuring gross margin, the company is maintaining its operating margin guidance due to the strength of its operating model, combined with its six- point tariff mitigation plan.

We update our estimates following 2Q25 results. We are now modeling FY25 comparable sales growth of \(+3.1\%\) (vs. \(+2.2\%\) prior), with operating margins of \(17.9\%\) (vs. \(17.7\%\) prior). Our FY25 EPS estimate decreases to \(8.52\) from \(8.57\) prior, and our FY26/FY27 EPS estimates change slightly by \(+0.4\% / - 0.2\%\) to \(9.42 / 10.36\) , respectively.
Exhibit 4: WSM Estimate Change Summary In \(5mm\) , except per-share data
Source: Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

We are Neutral rated on WSM with a 12- month revised price target of \(203\) (vs. \(179\) prior) based on our higher downside/base/upside case relative P/E multiples of \(85\% /90\% /95\%\) (vs. \(80\% /85\% /90\%\) prior) given we are getting closer to a lower interest rate environment, which will likely increase demand, and a higher market multiple of \(23.1x\) (vs. \(22.2x\) prior).

Upside risks: the higher than historical level of demand that the home furnishings category saw during the pandemic could return if the housing market strengthens, especially as hybrid work culture remains more prominent; the company continues to maintain the majority of the meaningful gross margin expansion it underwent in 2020/21 and believes this is a structural change with a long- term operating margin in the mid to high teens, which could drive upside risk to our numbers; there are opportunities for market share gains given industry fragmentation and continued pressure in the department store channel, along with persistent retail pressures leading to bankruptcies (e.g., Pier 1)

Downside risks: inconsistent demand trends could continue to weigh on the comp, noting the share of wallet/pull- forward impact for the furniture category; margins could be pressured once WSM is no longer benefiting from freight tailwinds, or a promotional environment could weigh on margins; WSM is trading above its historical average at 21.6x NTM P/E, vs. its 3- year/5- year average of 14.5x/14.3x

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
